#X text 291 379 This is a low random frequency modulation at 0.5 hertz \, but we'll see now what happens when we have higher frequencies now and what happens to a single oscillator., f 24;
#X text 239 378 <-----;
#X text 23 29 In generally \, modulating a signal means applying any changes to it. In the context of computer music and synthesis \, we're talking about a modulating signal that controls a parameter \, such as amplitude as we'll see in this chapter \, but it's worth noting how in the previous examples we've also seen modulation in every case. For wavetable synthesis we had an example of low frequency random modulation to scan the waveforms. For additive synthesis we had low frequency frequency and amplitude modulation. In a similar fashio \, for Subtractive Synthesis we've seen filter modulation \, with envelopes \, LFOs and stuff... What makes this chapter on amplitude \, frequency and pulse width modulation special is that we now have "high" frequency modulation., f 68;
#X text 23 210 Nonetheless \, we can technically consider low frequency modulation of amplitude as a sort of amplitude modulation as well \, as there is no term to differentiate between them. Hence \, for starters \, let's revisit a low frequency modulation example \, with a multichannel oscillator (where each signal is a partial)., f 68;
#X text 537 90 Slow periodic amplitude modulations give us tremolo effects \, which is something we'll also see in this chapter., f 36;
#X obj 604 413 brown~;
#X obj 604 468 *~;
#X obj 604 502 out~;
#X text 537 156 Technically wise \, applying envelopes to the amplitude is also nothing but amplitude modulation! With a slow attack/release and different lines and shapes you can also consider it a 'low frequency' in terms that we're not applying fast changes to the sound. And note how things like slow random modulations \, temolo effects and evelope shapes to affect the timbre significantly and can be efficient and interesting sound design tools., f 36;
